A Market for Almost Everything
Used to be, a man wanted something to eat, he grew it or killed it and cook=
ed it for himself.=C2=A0
Millennia ago, there was no market for food, no buyers or sellers. A man co=
uldn=E2=80=99t, at the end of a long day, say, =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s just =
order tonight.=E2=80=9D Couldn=E2=80=99t even go to a grocery store to get =
the ingredients and cook it himself. There was no price he could pay for a =
meal but his own direct labor.=C2=A0
Today, we do this:=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s a real screenshot from my phone yesterday, and look, I fully=
 admit $29.06 is an absurd amount of money to pay for a dozen donuts, but I=
 had a choice:
Not get the donuts.=C2=A0
Spend half an hour wrangling the kids into the double stroller, walking to =
Dunkin=E2=80=99, ordering the donuts, and carrying them back home.=C2=A0
Just order the donuts and pay the delivery fee, service fee, and tip.=C2=A0
It was Puja=E2=80=99s birthday and she loves Dunkin=E2=80=99 Donuts, so A w=
asn=E2=80=99t an option. I chose C.=C2=A0
As much as people love sharing screenshots of food delivery fees in horror,=
 there=E2=80=99s something kind of great about them.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s now a market =E2=80=93 I can pay some price to get what I w=
ant. It=E2=80=99s legible =E2=80=93 my time was clearly priced at the $9.76=
 fee + tip bundle. And it=E2=80=99s liquid =E2=80=93 as soon as I decided I=
 wanted the donuts, there was someone willing to get them for me for that $=
9.76, in less time than it would have taken me.=C2=A0
Something similar is happening, has happened, and will continue to happen e=
verywhere you look: donuts, dating, stocks, jobs, revenge [ https://link.sb=
stck.com/redirect/761eccf5-b568-45ee-9cc3-a0503423d874?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s like a law of physics, or at least a law of capitalism:=C2=A0
Markets emerge for almost everything and become more liquid and legible ove=
r time.=C2=A0
Take views. On Friday, I was sitting there minding my business, when I got =
an email from X:
The company formerly known as Twitter paid me $3,523.35 for tweeting, somet=
hing I=E2=80=99ve been addicted to doing, for free, for years. That=E2=80=
=99s like a pack-a-day smoker waking up one morning to a big check from Mar=
lboro simply for smoking a pack-a-day. (Tweeter beware: that does actually =
happen sometimes [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/1102a092-a0cf-449d-af5c=
-157d87582268?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ], but when it does, it=E2=80=99s because Marlboro gave you cancer.)=
=C2=A0
Twitter has always been very valuable to me. Not Boring and Not Boring Capi=
tal probably wouldn=E2=80=99t exist without it. But that value was indirect=
:=C2=A0
Find an idea on Twitter, write about it, get more subscribers, sell more sp=
onsorships.=C2=A0
Or, newsletter shared on Twitter, more people subscribe, sell more sponsors=
hips.=C2=A0
Or, tweet something insightful, impress a potential LP who invests in the f=
und.=C2=A0
Or, tweet something about an industry I=E2=80=99m exploring, find a founder=
 we invest in.=C2=A0
I couldn=E2=80=99t have told you how much a view was worth. It wasn=E2=80=
=99t legible. And I couldn=E2=80=99t convert views directly into dollars. I=
t wasn=E2=80=99t liquid.=C2=A0
With Creator Payouts, it=E2=80=99s both. Roughly 15 million views at $0.000=
2 per view, paid directly into my account.=C2=A0
That combination =E2=80=93 legibility and liquidity =E2=80=93 is as allurin=
g as it is dangerous. It can tempt you into short-term moves at the expense=
 of long-term ones.=C2=A0
In The Great Online Game [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/7c54993a-f09e-4=
c33-b45b-c35ce3f3cff9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ], I wrote that, =E2=80=9CMedium-level Twitter is Threads and=
 engagement hacks. Twitter Mastery is indistinguishable from an ongoing gam=
e.=E2=80=9D
Now, medium-level Twitter, the threads and engagement hacks, gets you paid.=
 There are playbooks you can follow and accounts you can copy to build a fo=
llowing and produce mindless view fodder as predictably as a delivery perso=
n can make $9.76 for bringing me donuts.=C2=A0
You do so at the risk of getting stuck on medium, polishing away exactly th=
e unique and weird curiosities and obsessions that might attract the other =
people with the same weird curiosities and obsessions. And you do so at the=
 risk of being labeled, subconsciously, as an engagement hacker by the very=
 people whose engagement might matter most to you.=C2=A0
As markets get more liquid and legible, it=E2=80=99s too easy to be mid, to=
 be the rat in Steve Cutts=E2=80=99 Happiness:=C2=A0
But that=E2=80=99s not you! Resisting the temptation is more valuable now, =
too, because it=E2=80=99s harder.=C2=A0
As people contort themselves to please the algorithm for short-term payouts=
, there=E2=80=99s even more of the less legible, less liquid, but ultimatel=
y more important long-term value up for grabs for you if you continue to ju=
st be yourself and talk about whatever lights your fire, algorithm be damne=
d.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t get me wrong. I think it=E2=80=99s great that Twitter is shar=
ing revenue with the creators who drive it, and I=E2=80=99ll happily take t=
he money. I got donuts to buy. And I love that some people are making more =
money from tweeting than they do in their day job; what a world!=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s just that Twitter is an easy toy example to make a bigger poin=
t:=C2=A0
It's useful to be aware of the trade-offs and incentives pulling at you as =
(almost) everything turns into a liquid and legible market.
Liquid and legible markets are, on balance, a great thing. They=E2=80=99re =
a sign of progress=E2=80=99 march.=C2=A0
The market for sending things to space [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/5=
41aa38a-861c-4895-9ca7-5e33aa8b9326?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is now liquid and legible. The market for com=
pute [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/54326cdb-27c7-45d2-a492-5d649f3fbaa=
6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is n=
ow liquid and legible. The market for  [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/9=
67340aa-1046-4e46-93b6-cb4fb56ae6b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]intelligence [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirec=
t/967340aa-1046-4e46-93b6-cb4fb56ae6b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is even becoming more liquid and legible.=
=C2=A0
Nine times out of ten, the right move is to simply and gratefully take adva=
ntage of that legibility and liquidity. Buy a SpaceX rideshare instead of b=
uilding your own rocket. Use AWS instead of racking your own servers. Plug =
in OpenAI=E2=80=99s API instead of building your own foundation model. Hell=
, go farm views on Twitter to make the money to do that thing you really wa=
nt to do, that only you can do.=C2=A0
If the liquid and legible market is in something that=E2=80=99s not core to=
 who you are or what you want to do, by all means, squeeze that liquidity a=
nd legibility for all they=E2=80=99re worth. If paying someone $9.76 to pic=
k up donuts means I get to spend 30 minutes writing or playing with my kids=
, I=E2=80=99ll make that trade all day. If Twitter wants to pay me to do ex=
actly what I=E2=80=99d do anyway, awesome.=C2=A0
Just beware of the temptation to take the liquid and legible path ten times=
 out of ten.=C2=A0
As markets become more liquid and legible, beta improves while alpha erodes=
=2E The average person in those mark=
ets is better off, but it=E2=80=99s harde=
r to outperform. It=E2=80=99s easier than ever to make $1,000 by tweeting t=
hreads, and harder than ever to stand out as unique by doing so.=C2=A0
Know what you want to stand out for, how you=E2=80=99re different [ https:/=
/link.sbstck.com/redirect/67a77d59-3b6f-41ff-9a27-4de38f933466?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], what you can do t=
hat no one else can that can=E2=80=99t be captured by an algorithm or simpl=
e market signals, at least not yet.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a market for almost everything.=C2=A0
The most valuable things will always be the ones that are hardest to price.
Thanks to Dan [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/650719e4-61b6-4fd3-9f8d-4c=
783b041532?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] and Puja [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a3bd13d6-e57a-4e8b-beb3-86=
c19c3b5b48?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with the Weekly Dose.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

